) RETURNING id INTO v_mod4;

INSERT INTO course_lessons (id, module_id, title, content, sort_order) VALUES
('ss-4-1', v_mod4, 'Short Sales with Multiple Liens', E'# Short Sales with Multiple Liens\n\nMany short sale properties have more than one mortgage or lien. Managing multiple lienholders is one of the most challenging aspects of short sale transactions.\n\n## Common Multiple Lien Scenarios\n\n### Second Mortgage or HELOC\nThe most common scenario. The homeowner has:\n- A first mortgage (the primary loan)\n- A second mortgage or home equity line of credit (HELOC)\n- Both lienholders must agree to release their liens for the sale to close\n\n### Tax Liens\n- Federal or state tax liens attached to the property\n- Must be satisfied or subordinated for clear title\n- The IRS may negotiate a lien release for less than the full amount\n\n### HOA Liens\n- Unpaid homeowner association assessments\n- HOA may have super-lien priority in some states\n- Must be negotiated as part of the closing\n\n### Judgment Liens\n- Court judgments against the seller that have attached to the property\n- Can be from lawsuits, unpaid debts, or other legal actions\n- Must be negotiated or the judgment creditor must release the lien\n\n## The First Lien vs. Second Lien Dynamic\n\nUnderstanding the leverage dynamics is crucial:\n\n**The first lienholder has the most power** because:\n- They are in first position and get paid first in any sale\n- They control the foreclosure process\n- In foreclosure, the second lien is often wiped out entirely\n\n**The second lienholder has limited leverage** because:\n- If the first forecloses, the second lien is extinguished\n- They will receive nothing in a foreclosure\n- A short sale gives them something (even if it is much less than owed)\n\n**This dynamic is your negotiating tool.** The second lienholder should prefer a small payoff in a short sale over getting nothing in a foreclosure.\n\n## Negotiating with Second Lienholders\n\n### What First Lienholders Allow\nThe first lienholder typically limits how much of the sale proceeds can go to the second lienholder:\n\n- **Fannie Mae loans:** Up to $12,000 to second lienholders\n- **Freddie Mac loans:** Up to $12,000 to second lienholders\n- **FHA loans:** Specific guidelines vary\n- **Private investors:** Varies — may be more or less flexible\n\n### Common Second Lien Outcomes\n\n1. **Accept the allowed payoff** — The second lienholder agrees to accept the amount the first lien allows (e.g., $6,000 on a $50,000 HELOC)\n2. **Negotiate a higher payoff** — The second lienholder demands more, and the first lienholder may allow it to close the deal\n3. **Seller contribution** — The seller agrees to make a separate payment to the second lienholder\n4. **Promissory note** — The second lienholder releases the lien in exchange for an unsecured promissory note from the seller\n5. **Full release with deficiency waiver** — Best case: the second lienholder accepts the payoff and waives any future claim\n6. **Refusal** — Worst case: the second lienholder refuses to release, blocking the sale\n\n### When the Second Lienholder Refuses\n\nIf the second lienholder will not cooperate:\n- Explain that foreclosure by the first will result in zero recovery\n- Ask if there is a specific amount that would secure their cooperation\n- Involve the seller''s attorney to negotiate directly\n- Consider whether the seller can make a cash contribution\n- In some cases, the first lienholder will increase the allowable payoff to get the deal done\n\n## Managing the Approval Process\n\nWith multiple lienholders, the approval process multiplies:\n\n1. Submit the short sale package to the **first lienholder**\n2. Once the first lienholder approves, submit to the **second lienholder** with the first''s approval letter\n3. Negotiate the second lienholder''s payoff\n4. If there are additional liens (tax, HOA, judgment), negotiate each one\n5. All lienholders must agree before closing can occur\n\n**Timeline impact:** Each additional lienholder can add 30-60 days to the process.\n\n## Documentation for Multiple Liens\n\nFor each lienholder, you will need:\n- Separate authorization to release information\n- Current payoff statements showing the balance\n- The lienholder''s short sale department contact information\n- Their specific document requirements\n- Their approval letter with terms\n\n## Strategies for Success\n\n1. **Identify all liens early** — run a comprehensive title search before listing\n2. **Contact all lienholders simultaneously** — do not wait for sequential approvals if possible\n3. **Know the guidelines** — understand what each first lienholder allows for junior liens\n4. **Be creative** — there are often multiple ways to structure a payoff that works for everyone\n5. **Stay organized** — track the status of each lienholder''s approval separately\n6. **Use leverage** — remind junior lienholders of their foreclosure risk\n\n## Summary\n\nMultiple liens add significant complexity to short sales, but they are not insurmountable. Understanding the leverage dynamics, knowing the guidelines, and negotiating persistently with each lienholder are the keys to getting all parties to the closing table.', 1),

('ss-4-2', v_mod4, 'Government Loan Short Sales: FHA, VA, and USDA', E'# Government Loan Short Sales: FHA, VA, and USDA\n\nShort sales on government-backed loans follow different rules and processes than conventional loans. Each program has specific requirements that agents must understand.\n\n## FHA Short Sales (HUD Pre-Foreclosure Sale Program)\n\nFHA loans are insured by the Federal Housing Administration and serviced by FHA-approved lenders.\n\n### Key FHA Short Sale Rules\n- The borrower must be in default or default is imminent\n- The property must be the borrower''s primary residence (or was at time of default)\n- The borrower must demonstrate financial hardship\n- The lender must determine that foreclosure would result in a greater loss than the short sale\n\n### FHA Approval Process\n1. The servicer evaluates the borrower for all loss mitigation options (modification first)\n2. If modification is not viable, the servicer can approve a short sale\n3. FHA has specific guidelines for acceptable sale prices (typically must net at least 88% of appraised value)\n4. The servicer submits the case to HUD for approval\n5. HUD reviews and issues a decision\n\n### FHA-Specific Considerations\n- **Appraisal requirement:** FHA often requires a full appraisal rather than just a BPO\n- **Commission limits:** FHA allows reasonable and customary real estate commissions (typically up to 6%)\n- **Deficiency:** FHA loans are generally **non-recourse** for the borrower after a short sale (the FHA insurance fund absorbs the loss)\n- **Timeline:** FHA short sales can be slower due to the additional HUD review layer\n- **Condition standards:** FHA has minimum property condition requirements for the buyer''s new FHA loan (if applicable)\n\n### FHA Connection Portal\nServicers use the **FHA Connection system** to process short sales. The listing agent does not have direct access but should understand that this is part of the process.\n\n## VA Short Sales (Compromise Sale)\n\nVA loans are guaranteed by the Department of Veterans Affairs.\n\n### Key VA Short Sale Rules\n- The veteran must be in default or facing imminent default\n- The VA must agree that the short sale is in the best interest of the government\n- The VA will evaluate whether the veteran can repay any deficiency\n\n### VA Approval Process\n1. The servicer evaluates all alternatives (modification, forbearance, etc.)\n2. If a short sale is the best option, the servicer contacts the VA Regional Loan Center\n3. The VA reviews the case and determines the acceptable terms\n4. The VA may require specific conditions for approval\n\n### VA-Specific Considerations\n- **VA entitlement:** A VA short sale may affect the veteran''s future VA loan entitlement. The veteran may need to repay the VA''s loss to restore full entitlement.\n- **Deficiency:** The VA may or may not waive the deficiency depending on the circumstances\n- **Compromise claim:** The VA pays a claim to the servicer for the guaranteed portion of the loss\n- **Impact on future VA loans:** Veterans can use remaining entitlement or restored entitlement for future purchases, but the short sale''s impact on entitlement varies by case\n\n### Special Protections for Veterans\n- The Servicemembers Civil Relief Act (SCRA) provides protections for active-duty military members\n- Interest rate caps, foreclosure delays, and other protections may apply\n- Agents should be aware of SCRA protections when working with active-duty clients\n\n## USDA Short Sales\n\nUSDA Rural Development loans are guaranteed by the U.S. Department of Agriculture.\n\n### Key USDA Short Sale Rules\n- Similar hardship and default requirements to FHA and VA\n- The property must be in an eligible rural area\n- USDA must approve the short sale terms\n\n### USDA-Specific Considerations\n- USDA short sales are less common but follow a similar process\n- The USDA guarantee program absorbs losses similarly to FHA insurance\n- Deficiency policies vary by program and circumstance\n- Timeline can be lengthy due to USDA review requirements\n\n## Conventional Loans: Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac\n\nWhile not government loans, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac have standardized short sale programs:\n\n### Fannie Mae Standard Short Sale\n- Borrower must have a financial hardship\n- Property can be primary residence, second home, or investment property\n- Servicer has delegated authority to approve in many cases\n- Relocation assistance of up to $3,000 may be available\n- Deficiency is typically waived for primary residences\n\n### Freddie Mac Standard Short Sale\n- Similar requirements to Fannie Mae\n- Uses the same general process\n- Deficiency waiver policies align with Fannie Mae\n\n## Agent Tips for Government Loan Short Sales\n\n1. **Identify the loan type early** — ask the seller or check with the servicer\n2. **Understand the specific program rules** for that loan type\n3. **Expect longer timelines** due to additional government review layers\n4. **Know the deficiency rules** — they vary significantly by loan type\n5. **Educate your clients** about how their specific loan type affects the process\n6. **Connect veterans with VA loan counselors** who understand entitlement implications\n\n## Summary\n\nGovernment-backed loans have their own short sale programs with specific rules, timelines, and implications. Agents who understand the differences between FHA, VA, USDA, and conventional short sales can better serve their clients and navigate the additional complexity these transactions involve.', 2),

('ss-4-3', v_mod4, 'Short Sales During Active Foreclosure', E'# Short Sales During Active Foreclosure\n\nOne of the most time-sensitive scenarios in real estate is pursuing a short sale while the clock is ticking on a foreclosure sale. This requires urgency, strategy, and close coordination with all parties.\n\n## The Race Against Foreclosure\n\nWhen a homeowner is in foreclosure AND pursuing a short sale, two timelines are running simultaneously:\n\n- **Short sale timeline:** Package submission, lender review, BPO, approval (60-120+ days)\n- **Foreclosure timeline:** Notice of default, notice of sale, auction date (varies by state, typically 90-180 days)\n\nIf the foreclosure auction happens before the short sale is approved, the short sale is dead.\n\n## Judicial vs. Non-Judicial Foreclosure States\n\n### Judicial Foreclosure States\n- Foreclosure goes through the court system\n- Typically slower (6-18 months)\n- More opportunities to delay or postpone\n- The seller''s attorney can request continuances\n- Examples: New York, New Jersey, Florida, Illinois, Ohio\n\n### Non-Judicial Foreclosure States\n- Foreclosure happens outside the court system\n- Typically faster (3-6 months)\n- Harder to delay without lender cooperation\n- The trustee or sheriff handles the sale\n- Examples: California, Texas, Georgia, Arizona, Virginia\n\nThe type of foreclosure in your state directly affects how much time you have to complete the short sale.\n\n## Getting the Foreclosure Postponed\n\nThe most critical task when a foreclosure date is looming:\n\n### Option 1: Request a Postponement from the Servicer\n- Contact the loss mitigation department and request that the foreclosure sale be postponed pending the short sale review\n- Provide evidence that the short sale package has been submitted and is being reviewed\n- Include the purchase agreement and buyer''s pre-approval\n- Many servicers will postpone if they believe the short sale will result in a better outcome\n\n### Option 2: The Seller''s Attorney Requests a Continuance\n- In judicial foreclosure states, the attorney can file a motion to continue the sale\n- Courts are often willing to grant continuances when a legitimate short sale is pending\n- Provide the attorney with documentation of the short sale progress\n\n### Option 3: Bankruptcy Filing\n- Filing for bankruptcy triggers an **automatic stay** that immediately halts the foreclosure\n- This is a last-resort option with significant consequences\n- The stay gives temporary breathing room to complete the short sale\n- The seller must understand the implications of a bankruptcy filing\n- Always involve an attorney in this decision\n\n### Option 4: Request Dual Tracking Prohibition\n- Many states and federal regulations (through the CFPB) restrict **dual tracking** — the practice of pursuing foreclosure while a short sale or modification is being reviewed\n- If the servicer is dual tracking in violation of these rules, the seller''s attorney can demand compliance\n- Document any dual tracking violations carefully\n\n## Timeline Management Strategies\n\n### Start Early\n- Begin the short sale process as soon as the seller contacts you\n- Don''t wait for a buyer — submit the seller''s hardship package to the lender immediately\n- Request a BPO or appraisal upfront to speed the review\n\n### Parallel Processing\n- Market the property while assembling the short sale package\n- Submit the package as soon as an offer is received\n- Contact junior lienholders simultaneously with the first lienholder\n- Prepare all closing documents in advance\n\n### Escalate Early\n- If the foreclosure date is within 60 days, escalate immediately\n- Request a supervisor or manager at the servicer\n- Send written requests for postponement via certified mail and email\n- Engage the seller''s attorney to send legal correspondence\n\n## What Happens If Foreclosure Is Not Postponed\n\nIf the lender refuses to postpone and the foreclosure sale proceeds:\n\n- **The short sale is terminated** — the property is sold at auction\n- **The buyer loses the deal** — their earnest money should be refunded per the short sale contingency\n- **The seller faces foreclosure** — with all the associated credit and legal consequences\n- **In some cases:** The auction is postponed at the last minute (foreclosure dates are frequently continued)\n\n## Dual Tracking Rules\n\nThe **CFPB (Consumer Financial Protection Bureau)** has rules that limit dual tracking:\n\n- If the borrower submits a **complete loss mitigation application** more than 37 days before a foreclosure sale, the servicer must evaluate it before proceeding with foreclosure\n- The servicer cannot move for a foreclosure judgment or conduct a sale while the application is being evaluated\n- If a short sale is part of the loss mitigation evaluation, it should be protected under these rules\n\n**Note:** These rules apply to the first lien servicer and may not prevent junior lienholders from taking action.\n\n## Agent Best Practices\n\n1. **Know your state''s foreclosure timeline** — how long does the process take?\n2. **Check the foreclosure status immediately** when taking a short sale listing\n3. **Get the foreclosure sale date** — call the servicer or check public records\n4. **Submit the short sale package as quickly as possible** — every day counts\n5. **Request postponement in writing** at the first sign of a timeline conflict\n6. **Work closely with the seller''s attorney** on legal options\n7. **Keep the buyer informed** about the foreclosure risk\n8. **Have a plan B** for the buyer in case the foreclosure proceeds\n\n## Summary\n\nShort sales during active foreclosure require speed, strategy, and close coordination. Understanding your state''s foreclosure process, requesting timely postponements, and leveraging dual tracking protections can save the deal. When time is short, every day matters.', 3);

